attributes.title: How To Become A Good Sounding Drummer
Exploring The Grooves Of Harvey Mason
Building Open-Ended Facility On The Drums

attributes.value: Being able to play the drums open-handed will open up a whole new world of creative and musical possibilities. Claus Hessler will introduce you to the concept of open-handed drumming and how it can be applied to orchestrations, rudiments, and linear drumming.

If you find yourself playing the same hi-hat patterns in all of your grooves, this is the course for you! This course will explore funk hi-hat variations, colorful hi-hat patterns, and some left foot hi-hat feels. Gulli Briem will also breakdown a famous groove from "Icebreaker" by Mezzoforte.

Indian rhythms can be quite intimidating for anyone who hasn't studied them at length. As a result, many drummers end up not following a route that's not as demanding as it first seems and is filled with great ideas and concepts for drum-set applications. With that in mind, Pete Lockett put together this introductory Course on Indian rhythms so you can learn some of its basic patterns, or phrases, how to count them and combine them into different ideas.

In this Course, Henrique de Almeida will teach you how to build a Conga groove, and some variations that make use of toms and a cowbell, that you'll be able to take and practice along a jam track written specifically for this Course.

If you're looking for a brand new challenge or just want to expand your knowledge of rudiments, this is the Course for you. In it, you'll learn how to play three Swiss rudiments: the doubl, the flammed 5 stroke roll, and the final stroke of 7. As a bonus, Claus will show you how to apply them on the kit and as patterns within a Swiss snare solo known as "The Morgenstreich".

This Course is all about getting you comfortable playing triplet patterns in a variety of ways, by using the 16th-note beats and fills you already know how to play, as inspiration. With the help of Jeff Salem, you'll learn rudimental triplet fills with single strokes, flams, and paradiddles, and how to create your own triplet beats, linear patterns and broken hi-hat beats.

Drum and bass is a relatively young genre of music that can be quite challenging and hard to get into. If you've been wanting to learn how to play drums to this style of music, look no further. In this Course, Peter Szendofi will teach you the history of drum and bass, beginner to intermediate beats, fills, as well technique and tuning tips.

No matter how complex and fast your playing is, if you're not sounding awesome, all your technical prowess will be for not - it's also what will make or break you as a professional musician. So working on your sound, on how you hit the drums and mix them in real time, is as important as working on your technique and overall facility around the drums. So in this Course, Todd Sucherman will teach you to become a good sounding drummer so you can be as musical and hirable as possible.

Quintuplets and septuplets are some of the most underused subdivisions in our rhythmic arsenal. This is quite unfortunate because the potential for awesome groove and fill creation is there. With that in mind, Anika Nilles put this Course together for you so you can learn how to internalize these subdivisions and combine them with other ones, with the goal of using them musically.

Soloing can be quite daunting for those who don't have much experience with it. However, no matter the skill level you are at or how simple your patterns are, you'll actually be able to create musical and interesting solos with the help of this Course. Dafnis Prieto is renown as one of the best soloists in the world of drumming and an incredible teacher. With the help of a few simple strategies, he'll have you soloing in no time.

Live gigs have a ton more to them than just setting up your gear on stage to play your songs in front of an audience. The amount of things that can go wrong on stage and the options that can make your band and show stand out are staggering. Because of it, Chip Ritter put together this Course to help you organize incredible live shows by learning how to create a show plan, set up the stage and your kit, learn how to be a showman and how to keep improving your performances with post-gig reviews.

Creating effective and great-sounding drum parts for songs requires a lot of sensibility and experience. To help you fast-track your development in this area, Jason Sutter will be discussing the importance of musical phrasing when creating drum parts, by analysing and breaking down Smash Mouth's cover of The Kinks' "All Day and All of the Night".

Rudiments can be used in way more ways than just exercises to improve your hand technique - and that's exactly what this Course will teach you how to do. In it, Todd Sucherman will take you through four different concepts that will teach you how to make any rudiment applicable to the drum-set as a beat, fill or solo idea.

The single paradiddle is one of the most popular drum rudiments out there, making it quite hard for anyone to use it in very unique ways. So in this Course and with the help of Adam Marko, you'll learn how to build your own voice on the kit with the single paradiddle by learning to play the hybrid paradiddle, and how to use it to enhance your playing within different styles of music.

Reggae is a very cool style of drumming to learn, especially when it comes to the type of drum fills usually associated with it. In this Course, Issah Contractor will teach you 15 rhythmically varied reggae patterns that work great either as intro patterns or drum fills, and that you'll be able to apply to a play-along by the end of this Course.

Dali Mraz showcases a high level of proficiency on the kit at a very young age. This comes to show what a well thought out practice routine can do for one's development. In this Course, Dali is going to share his practice method with you so you can develop your skills as quickly as possible and with the same high level of quality.

In this Course, Harvey Mason will teach you how to play grooves he came up with for some of the most successful songs he recorded drums for. This includes Herbie Hancock's "Chameleon", Seal's "Kiss From A Rose", George Benson's "Breezin'", and Seals and Crofts' "Diamond Girl".

Kaz Rodriguez is very well known in the music industry as naturally gifted when it comes to creating moving music and coming up with insanely groovy drum parts. In this Course, he took all that knowledge and used it to create musical exercises to help you improve many aspects of your core drumming abilities in a fun and inspirational way.

Creating drum parts on the spot is very daunting if you've never worked that much on it or on developing great facility around the kit. This Course is all about teaching you how to develop this type of freedom on the drums, so you're able to play anything you want, any time you want and in a way that complements the music you're playing to, beautifully.

In this Course, Tommy Igoe is going to expose you to some of the musical traps he purposely created when putting together "Groove Essentials", so you can take full advantage of this educational package to become the best musician possible.
